{"id":"2205.04571","submitter":"Xinbo Ai","authors":"Xinbo Ai","title":"Adjust Pearson's r to Measure Nonlinear Dependence","comments":"59 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"stat.OT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  As the most commonly used correlation statistic, Pearson's r is generally\nconsidered as a measure only for linear dependence. The use of Pearson's r has\nbeen strongly discouraged in nonlinear scenarios. Recent research shows that\nthis opinion is myth and Pearson's r should not be ruled out a priori for\nmeasuring nonlinear monotonic relationships. We find that Pearson's r does have\npotential to measure nonlinear dependence as long as the relationships are\nmonotonic, it just underestimates them. We derive a new inequality which is\ntighter than the famous Cauchy-Schwarz Inequality, leverage it to adjust the\nunderestimation, and propose a new correlation statistic, i.e., rearrangement\ncorrelation. The rearrangement correlation is able to capture arbitrary\nmonotonic relationships, both linear and nonlinear ones. It reverts to\nPearson's r in linear scenarios, and to Spearman's rho when calculated on\nranks. Investigations on simulated and real-life scenarios show that the\nrearrangement correlation is more accurate in measuring nonlinear monotonic\ndependence, and more powerful in testing nonlinear monotonic dependence than\nclassical correlation statistics, and other recently proposed measures. Thus,\nPearson's r is a gold measure not only for linear dependence, but also for\nnonlinear monotonic dependence, if adjusted.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 9 May 2022 21:33:15 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 30 May 2022 07:06:47 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 15 Jun 2022 06:37:02 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 3 Aug 2022 13:02:14 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Wed, 31 May 2023 00:10:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-06-01"}
